dataset.display: Estimated Annual Rate - Adults 30 Yrs and Older
dataset.measure: Estimated Annual Rate - Adults 30 Yrs and Older
dataset.how_calculated: Estimated annual number of all-cause deaths associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to modeled natural background. Estimate is calculated using the chronic all-cause mortality risk estimate from a comprehensive study by Krewski et al 2009. The rate is the number of deaths attributable to PM2.5 among residents (30 years and older), divided by the population of residents (30 years and older) expressed as cases per 100,000 residents.
dataset.discription: New York City Bureau of Vital Statistics; United States Census ,USEPA Air Quality System; Krewski D, et al. (2009) HEI Research Report 140. Health Effects Institute, Boston, MA

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.
